  <!-- PLAIN ENGLISH GLOSSARY -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">📖 Plain English Glossary</div>
    <div class="card-sub">The terms your technical team will use — and what they actually mean</div>
    <table class="tbl">
      <thead><tr><th>Technical Term</th><th>What It Actually Means</th><th>Why It Matters to You</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>LLM</strong></td><td>The AI "brain" — software trained on enormous amounts of text that can read, write, and reason</td><td>This is what you're buying/building — the core engine</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Local LLM</strong></td><td>The AI brain runs on computers you own, in your office or server room</td><td>Your data never leaves — critical for privacy</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Parameters / Billions</strong></td><td>How big the brain is. 70B = a very large, capable brain. 7B = smaller, faster, less accurate</td><td>Bigger = better quality but needs more expensive hardware</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>VRAM / GPU</strong></td><td>The special memory and processor inside a graphics card that runs AI much faster than a normal computer chip</td><td>Determines which AI models you can run and how fast</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>RAG</strong></td><td>"Retrieval-Augmented Generation" — connecting the AI to your documents so it can answer questions about your business specifically</td><td>This is what makes AI useful for your specific situation, not just general knowledge</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Quantization</strong></td><td>Shrinking the AI model to use less memory, with a slight quality trade-off (like compressing a photo — still recognisable but less sharp)</td><td>Lets you run bigger, better models on smaller hardware</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Fine-tuning</strong></td><td>Training the AI specifically on your data, your style, your terminology — like teaching a new hire about how your company works</td><td>Makes the AI significantly better at your specific tasks</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Hallucination</strong></td><td>When the AI confidently states something that is completely wrong or made up</td><td>Critical risk — always verify AI outputs in business-critical contexts</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Context window</strong></td><td>How much information the AI can "hold in its head" at once — like short-term memory</td><td>If your documents are very long, you need a model with a bigger context window</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Inference</strong></td><td>The moment the AI actually generates a response — "running" the model</td><td>Faster inference = quicker answers for your team</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Open source / Open weight</strong></td><td>The AI model is freely available to download and run — like free software</td><td>No licensing fees; you own your deployment</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Apache 2.0 / MIT</strong></td><td>Types of free licences that allow commercial use — the safest licences for businesses</td><td>Check this before deploying any model commercially</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Ollama / LM Studio</strong></td><td>Software that makes it easy to download and run local AI models (like an app store for AI models)</td><td>The simplest way to get started with local AI</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Vector database</strong></td><td>A special filing system that stores your documents in a way the AI can search through very quickly</td><td>Required for RAG — connects your documents to the AI</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

